The female of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="MAVROMOUSTAKIS" baseAuthorityYear="1954" box="[543,690,1619,1640]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Pseudoanthidium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="canariense">
<emphasis box="[543,690,1619,1640]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">P. canariense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be distinguished from other members of this complex by the following combination of characters: punctation on terga comparatively coarse, as large or larger than punctation on mesonotum, with shiny interspaces between punctures; largest punctures on black part of scutellum approximately equal in diameter to those of largest punctures on 
<collectionCode box="[464,483,1833,1854]" name="Tavera, Department of Geology and Geophysics" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">T</collectionCode>
2; maculations on head, mesosoma and metasoma dark orange; shiny spaces between punctures on 
<collectionCode box="[1077,1095,1525,1546]" name="Tavera, Department of Geology and Geophysics" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">T</collectionCode>
3 narrow, less than one-quarter of a puncture wide; hairs on inside of third basitarsus dark brown and with individual hairs mostly thicker than hairs on outside surface. Colour of maculations orange-yellow (
<figureCitation box="[1000,1095,1647,1669]" captionStart="Figure 25" captionStartId="33.[161,242,1400,1422]" captionTargetBox="[323,1283,195,1360]" captionTargetId="figure-197@33.[323,1283,195,1360]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="Figure 25. A, Pseudoanthidium canariense, female (Santa Cruz de Tenerife, Canary Islands); B, P. tropicum, female (Bandar Abbas, Iran); C, P. canariense, male (Santa Cruz de Tenerife, Canary Islands); D, P. tropicum, male (Bandar Abbas, Iran); E, T7, P. canariense (Santa Cruz de Tenerife, Canary Islands); F, T7, P. tropicum (Bandar Abbas, Iran)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5817332" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5817332/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Fig. 25A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[827,1443,1710,1885]" lastBlockId="34.[145,762,197,526]" lastPageId="34" lastPageNumber="35" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis box="[827,1017,1710,1732]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Diagnosis male:</emphasis>
The male of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="MAVROMOUSTAKIS" baseAuthorityYear="1954" box="[1191,1347,1711,1732]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Pseudoanthidium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="canariense">
<emphasis box="[1191,1347,1711,1732]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">P. canariense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be distinguished from other members of this complex by the following combination of characters: gonostylus approximately parallel-sided and unnotched at apex (
<figureCitation box="[835,928,1833,1855]" captionStart="Figure 23" captionStartId="31.[163,242,1341,1363]" captionTargetBox="[243,1363,195,1302]" captionTargetId="figure-27@31.[243,1363,195,1302]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="Figure 23. Gonostyli. A, Pseudoanthidium palestinicum (Nahal Keziv, Israel); B, P. cribratum (Karatau, Kazakhstan); C, P. canariense (Santa Cruz de Tenerife, Canary Islands); D, P. tropicum (Bandar Abbas, Iran); E, P. kaspareki (Side, Turkey); F, P. rozeni (Hanna, Pakistan)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5817324" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5817324/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Fig. 23C</figureCitation>
); lateral comb on S5 small, with longest teeth shorter than maximal width of hind basitarsus; posterior, premarginal brush on S3 with hairs hooked at tips; shiny, hairless zone on S3 between posterior premarginal brush of hairs and anterior zone of dense, velvety pilosity very short, about one-third of the width of the sternum, dark, chevron-shaped, without medial extension extending anteriorly along the midline of sternum; posterior margin of S2 medially emarginate, S2 otherwise covered in silvery pilosity except for a more or less hairless posterior margin. Colour of maculations orange-yellow (
<figureCitation box="[655,747,442,464]" captionStart="Figure 25" captionStartId="33.[161,242,1400,1422]" captionTargetBox="[323,1283,195,1360]" captionTargetId="figure-197@33.[323,1283,195,1360]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="Figure 25. A, Pseudoanthidium canariense, female (Santa Cruz de Tenerife, Canary Islands); B, P. tropicum, female (Bandar Abbas, Iran); C, P. canariense, male (Santa Cruz de Tenerife, Canary Islands); D, P. tropicum, male (Bandar Abbas, Iran); E, T7, P. canariense (Santa Cruz de Tenerife, Canary Islands); F, T7, P. tropicum (Bandar Abbas, Iran)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5817332" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5817332/files/figure.png" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Fig. 25C</figureCitation>
). Posterior margin of 
<collectionCode box="[371,388,474,495]" name="Tavera, Department of Geology and Geophysics" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">T</collectionCode>
7 with deep, nearly semi-circular emargination medially (
<figureCitation box="[408,498,504,526]" captionStart="Figure 25" captionStartId="33.[161,242,1400,1422]" captionTargetBox="[323,1283,195,1360]" captionTargetId="figure-197@33.[323,1283,195,1360]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="Figure 25. A, Pseudoanthidium canariense, female (Santa Cruz de Tenerife, Canary Islands); B, P. tropicum, female (Bandar Abbas, Iran); C, P. canariense, male (Santa Cruz de Tenerife, Canary Islands); D, P. tropicum, male (Bandar Abbas, Iran); E, T7, P. canariense (Santa Cruz de Tenerife, Canary Islands); F, T7, P. tropicum (Bandar Abbas, Iran)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5817332" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5817332/files/figure.png" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Fig. 25E</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
